* Screen orientation : Horizontal
* Video resolution : 256 x 240 pixels
* Screen refresh : 60.00&nbsp;Hz
* Palette Colors : 256
* Players : 2
* Control : 8-way joystick
* Buttons : 2

== Reception ==
In Japan, ''Game Machine'' listed ''Shootout'' on their August 15, 1985 issue as being the tenth most-successful table arcade unit of the month.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Game Machine's Best Hit Games 25 - テーブル型TVゲーム機 (Table Videos)|magazine=[[:ja:ゲームマシン|Game Machine]]|issue=266|publisher=[[:ja:アミューズメント通信社|Amusement Press, Inc.]]|date=15 August 1985|page=21|lang=ja}}</ref>

Mike Roberts and Steve Phipps of ''[[Computer Gamer]]'' magazine reviewed the game, giving it a positive review, calling it "a target shooting game with a difference." They noted that, in contrast to a standard shooting gallery with targets that don't fire back, the enemies in ''Shoutout'' fire back at the player while often taking cover and popping out from cover.<ref name="CG7">{{cite magazine |last1=Roberts |first1=Mike |last2=Phipps |first2=Steve |title=Coin-Op Connection |magazine=[[Computer Gamer]] |date=October 1985 |issue=7 |publisher=[[Argus Press]] |location=United Kingdom |pages=18–9 |url=https://archive.org/details/Computer_Gamer_Issue_07_1985-10_Argus_Press_GB/page/n17/mode/2up}}</ref>

Clare Edgeley of ''[[Computer and Video Games]]'' magazine gave it a positive review. She noted the enemies "crop up in the most unexpected places" and said it was "as much fun as" [[Sega]]'s ''[[Bank Panic]]'' (1984) and [[Nintendo]]'s ''[[Hogan's Alley (video game)|Hogan's Alley]]'' (1984). She concluded, "Take your pick, all three are great fun."<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Edgeley |first1=Clare |title=Arcade Action |magazine=[[Computer and Video Games]] |date=16 December 1985 |issue=51 (January 1986) |pages=54–5 |url=https://archive.org/details/cvg-magazine-051/page/n53/mode/2up}}</ref>

